  "objectives": "Objectives\r\nPractice preflight planning procedures for flying in the low-level environment.\r\nGain meaningful exposure to low-level navigation in preparation for Mission Phase.\r\nDiscuss task management, effects of airspeed, altitude, G-forces and bank angle in relation to time-to-impact.\r\nNotes:\r\nThe squadron manages the planning process to ensure students prepare maps for low-level missions and establishes a process to ensure all critical information on the IP and studentsâ€™ maps is identical when stepping for the mission.\r\nThe student uses DR navigation techniques / procedures (clock-to-map- to-ground) to maintain situational awareness and navigate the route.\r\nFly the first portion of the low-level sortie no lower than 1,000 ft. AGL. Step down to lower altitudes on subsequent legs if proficiency is demonstrated in altitude awareness / control, heading and airspeed control, timing, map reading, fuel procedures, turns and diversion awareness.\r\nIf possible, fly the VFR point-to-point Q4NXX sortie prior to the first low-level sortie.\r\nStudents may use GPS for all functions except course guidance. IPs use the GPS to maintain situational awareness on all off-station low- levels.",
